        </div>

        <div class="tab-content active">
            <h2>2024 SHAPE America National Physical Education Standards</h2>
            <p style="margin-bottom: 25px; color: var(--text-medium); font-size: 1.05em; line-height: 1.7;">
                Released in March 2024 after a multi-year revision process, SHAPE America's National Physical Education Standards define what a student should know and be able to do as a result of a highly effective physical education program. These standards provide a comprehensive framework for educators to deliver high-quality instruction and support every student's <strong>physical literacy journey</strong>â€”the ongoing process of developing the motivation, confidence, physical competence, knowledge, and understanding to value and engage in physical activity for life.
            </p>

            <div class="tips-box" style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #e8eef5 0%, #d4dce8 100%); border-left-color: #0f2044;">
                <div class="tips-title" style="color: #0f2044;">Key Changes in the 2024 Standards</div>
                <ul style="color: #1f2937;">
                    <li><strong>Physical Literacy Journey:</strong> Expanded terminology to emphasize the developmental, lifelong nature of becoming physically literate</li>
                    <li><strong>Grade-Span Learning Indicators:</strong> Shifted from grade-level outcomes to broader grade-span indicators (PreK-K, 1-2, 3-5, 6-8, 9-12) with learning progressions</li>
                    <li><strong>Four Standards:</strong> Streamlined from five to four standards for greater clarity and focus</li>
                    <li><strong>Holistic Development:</strong> Integrated emphasis on social-emotional learning, equity, inclusion, and whole-child development</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <!-- Standard 1 -->
            <div class="domain-card psychomotor" style="margin-top: 30px;">
                <div class="domain-badge">
                    <span class="domain-icon"></span>
                    Standard 1
                </div>
                <h3 style="margin-top: 0; color: var(--psychomotor); font-size: 1.8em;">Develops a variety of motor skills</h3>
                <div class="definition" style="font-size: 1em; font-style: italic; color: var(--text-medium); margin-bottom: 20px;">
                    Through learning experiences in physical education, the student develops motor skills across a variety of environments. Motor skills are a foundational part of child development and support the movements of everyday life. The development of motor skills contributes to an individual's physical literacy journey.
                </div>
                
                <div class="bloom-section">
                    <div class="bloom-title">Sample Grade-Span Learning Indicators</div>
                    <div class="grade-levels">
                        <div class="grade-card">
                            <div class="grade-level">PreK-K & Grades 1-2</div>
                            <div class="examples">
                                â€¢ Demonstrates locomotor skills (walk, run, hop, skip, gallop)<br>
                                â€¢ Performs non-locomotor skills (bend, twist, turn, balance)<br>
                                â€¢ Manipulates objects with hands and feet (throw, catch, kick, dribble)
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="grade-card">
                            <div class="grade-level">Grades 3-5</div>
                            <div class="examples">
                                â€¢ Demonstrates mature patterns in locomotor skills<br>
                                â€¢ Combines locomotor and manipulative skills in games<br>
                                â€¢ Performs movement sequences with rhythm and flow
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="grade-card">
                            <div class="grade-level">Grades 6-8</div>
                            <div class="examples">
                                â€¢ Demonstrates specialized skills in modified game play<br>
                                â€¢ Applies skills in dynamic, unpredictable environments<br>
                                â€¢ Refines technique in self-selected activities
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="grade-card">
                            <div class="grade-level">Grades 9-12</div>
                            <div class="examples">
                                â€¢ Demonstrates competency in two or more lifetime activities<br>
                                â€¢ Applies activity-specific skills in outdoor pursuits<br>
                                â€¢ Executes appropriate techniques in fitness training
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Standard 2 -->
            <div class="domain-card cognitive">
                <div class="domain-badge">
                    <span class="domain-icon"></span>
                    Standard 2
                </div>
                <h3 style="margin-top: 0; color: var(--cognitive); font-size: 1.8em;">Applies knowledge related to movement and fitness concepts</h3>
                <div class="definition" style="font-size: 1em; font-style: italic; color: var(--text-medium); margin-bottom: 20px;">
                    Through learning experiences in physical education, the student uses their knowledge of movement concepts, tactics, and strategies across a variety of environments. This knowledge helps the student become a more versatile and efficient mover. Additionally, the student applies knowledge of health-related and skill-related fitness to enhance their overall well-being.
                </div>
                
                <div class="bloom-section">
                    <div class="bloom-title">Sample Grade-Span Learning Indicators</div>
                    <div class="grade-levels">
                        <div class="grade-card">
                            <div class="grade-level">PreK-K & Grades 1-2</div>
                            <div class="examples">
                                â€¢ Identifies movement concepts (space, effort, relationships)<br>
                                â€¢ Recognizes how heart rate changes with activity<br>
                                â€¢ Identifies physical activities that contribute to fitness
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="grade-card">
                            <div class="grade-level">Grades 3-5</div>
                            <div class="examples">
                                â€¢ Applies movement concepts to improve performance<br>
                                â€¢ Demonstrates problem-solving strategies in games<br>
                                â€¢ Establishes goals related to fitness development
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="grade-card">
                            <div class="grade-level">Grades 6-8</div>
                            <div class="examples">
                                â€¢ Applies offensive and defensive strategies in games<br>
                                â€¢ Analyzes movement efficiency using biomechanical principles<br>
                                â€¢ Designs fitness plans using FITT principles
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="grade-card">
                            <div class="grade-level">Grades 9-12</div>
                            <div class="examples">
                                â€¢ Applies complex strategies in competitive settings<br>
                                â€¢ Evaluates fitness assessments and adjusts programs<br>
                                â€¢ Analyzes how nutrition and stress affect performance
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Standard 3 -->
            <div class="domain-card social">
                <div class="domain-badge">
                    <span class="domain-icon"></span>
                    Standard 3
                </div>
                <h3 style="margin-top: 0; color: var(--social); font-size: 1.8em;">Develops social skills through movement</h3>
                <div class="definition" style="font-size: 1em; font-style: italic; color: var(--text-medium); margin-bottom: 20px;">
                    Through learning experiences in physical education, students develop the social skills necessary to exhibit empathy and respect for others and foster and maintain relationships. In addition, students develop skills for communication, leadership, cultural awareness, and conflict resolution in a variety of physical activity settings.
                </div>
                
                <div class="bloom-section">
                    <div class="bloom-title">Sample Grade-Span Learning Indicators</div>
                    <div class="grade-levels">
                        <div class="grade-card">
                            <div class="grade-level">PreK-K & Grades 1-2</div>
                            <div class="examples">
                                â€¢ Works cooperatively with others in partner activities<br>
                                â€¢ Demonstrates respectful behaviors during movement<br>
                                â€¢ Makes safe choices with equipment and space
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="grade-card">
                            <div class="grade-level">Grades 3-5</div>
                            <div class="examples">
                                â€¢ Accepts and implements feedback from peers<br>
                                â€¢ Works cooperatively in small groups<br>
                                â€¢ Solves problems independently and with partners
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="grade-card">
                            <div class="grade-level">Grades 6-8</div>
                            <div class="examples">
                                â€¢ Demonstrates leadership by holding self and others accountable<br>
                                â€¢ Uses effective communication in dynamic situations<br>
                                â€¢ Applies conflict resolution strategies independently
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="grade-card">
                            <div class="grade-level">Grades 9-12</div>
                            <div class="examples">
                                â€¢ Facilitates group decision-making and goal-setting<br>
                                â€¢ Demonstrates cultural competence in diverse settings<br>
                                â€¢ Creates inclusive environments for all participants
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Standard 4 -->
            <div class="domain-card affective">
                <div class="domain-badge">
                    <span class="domain-icon"></span>
                    Standard 4
                </div>
                <h3 style="margin-top: 0; color: var(--affective); font-size: 1.8em;">Develops personal skills, identifies personal benefits of movement, and chooses to engage in physical activity</h3>
                <div class="definition" style="font-size: 1em; font-style: italic; color: var(--text-medium); margin-bottom: 20px;">
                    Through learning experiences in physical education, the student develops an understanding of how movement is relevant and important to their lives. The student identifies the personal benefits of movement and chooses to engage in a variety of developmentally appropriate physical activities. The development of personal skills contributes to an individual's physical literacy journey.
                </div>
                
                <div class="bloom-section">
                    <div class="bloom-title">Sample Grade-Span Learning Indicators</div>
                    <div class="grade-levels">
                        <div class="grade-card">
                            <div class="grade-level">PreK-K & Grades 1-2</div>
                            <div class="examples">
                                â€¢ Identifies physical activities they enjoy<br>
                                â€¢ Demonstrates effort and persistence when learning new skills<br>
                                â€¢ Describes how physical activity makes them feel
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="grade-card">
                            <div class="grade-level">Grades 3-5</div>
                            <div class="examples">
                                â€¢ Sets personal goals and monitors progress<br>
                                â€¢ Describes emotional responses to physical challenges<br>
                                â€¢ Chooses to participate in physical activity during free time
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="grade-card">
                            <div class="grade-level">Grades 6-8</div>
                            <div class="examples">
                                â€¢ Self-selects activities based on personal interests<br>
                                â€¢ Demonstrates self-management strategies (motivation, focus)<br>
                                â€¢ Advocates for physical activity opportunities at school
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="grade-card">
                            <div class="grade-level">Grades 9-12</div>
                            <div class="examples">
                                â€¢ Develops a personal philosophy of physical activity<br>
                                â€¢ Integrates regular physical activity into lifestyle<br>
                                â€¢ Identifies career opportunities related to physical activity
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="objective-section" style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #e0f5f5 0%, #c9eded 100%); border-color: var(--uncg-blue-green);">
                <h3 style="color: #2a7877;">Understanding the Standards Framework</h3>
                <p style="color: var(--text-medium); margin-bottom: 15px;">
                    The 2024 National Physical Education Standards work together as an interconnected framework:
                </p>
                <div class="formula-box" style="background: white; border-left-color: var(--uncg-blue-green);">
                    <div class="formula-parts" style="flex-direction: column; gap: 12px;">
                        <div style="padding: 0;">
                            <strong style="color: #2a7877;">Standards:</strong> Broad, overarching goals for PreK-12 physical education programs
                        </div>
                        <div style="padding: 0;">
                            <strong style="color: #2a7877;">Grade-Span Learning Indicators:</strong> Specific content areas and goals within five grade spans (PreK-K, 1-2, 3-5, 6-8, 9-12)
                        </div>
                        <div style="padding: 0;">
                            <strong style="color: #2a7877;">Learning Progressions:</strong> Sequential sample tasks showing skill development from PreK through high school
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <p style="color: var(--text-medium); font-size: 0.95em; margin-top: 15px; font-style: italic;">
                    <strong>Note:</strong> The standards are designed to be inclusive and accessible to all students, regardless of ability, age, class, gender, or race. They support each student's unique physical literacy journey.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="tab-content">
            <h2>The Four Learning Domains in Physical Education</h2>
            <p style="margin-bottom: 30px; color: var(--text-medium); font-size: 1.05em;">
                The 2024 SHAPE America National Physical Education Standards address learning across four interconnected domains. Each domain reflects different ways students learn, grow, and demonstrate competency. Understanding these domains helps teachers design comprehensive lessons that develop the whole child.
            </p>

            <!-- Psychomotor Domain -->
            <div class="domain-card psychomotor">
                <div class="domain-badge">
                    <span class="domain-icon"></span>
                    Psychomotor Domain
                </div>
                <div class="definition">
                    The psychomotor domain focuses on physical movement, motor skill development, and the body's ability to perform coordinated actions. This domain addresses how students move and develop physical competence through practice and refinement of skills.
                </div>
                
                <div class="bloom-section">
                    <div class="bloom-title">Bloom's Taxonomy in Action</div>
                    <div class="grade-levels">
                        <div class="grade-card">
                            <div class="grade-level">Elementary</div>
                            <div class="examples">
                                <strong>Remember:</strong> Recall the cues for an underhand throw<br>
                                <strong>Understand:</strong> Explain why we bend our knees when catching<br>
                                <strong>Apply:</strong> Demonstrate a mature galloping pattern during a game
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="grade-card">
                            <div class="grade-level">Middle School</div>
                            <div class="examples">
                                <strong>Analyze:</strong> Compare your forehand tennis stroke to proper form<br>
                                <strong>Evaluate:</strong> Assess which defensive position is most effective<br>
                                <strong>Create:</strong> Design a movement sequence combining three locomotor skills
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="grade-card">
                            <div class="grade-level">High School</div>
                            <div class="examples">
                                <strong>Apply:</strong> Execute advanced volleyball techniques in competitive play<br>
                                <strong>Analyze:</strong> Examine biomechanical principles in your golf swing<br>
                                <strong>Create:</strong> Choreograph an original fitness routine with varied intensity
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Cognitive Domain -->
            <div class="domain-card cognitive">
                <div class="domain-badge">
                    <span class="domain-icon"></span>
                    Cognitive Domain
                </div>
                <div class="definition">
                    The cognitive domain encompasses intellectual knowledge and understanding related to physical activity. Students develop critical thinking about movement concepts, rules, strategies, health benefits, and the principles underlying skilled performance.
                </div>
                
                <div class="bloom-section">
                    <div class="bloom-title">Bloom's Taxonomy in Action</div>
                    <div class="grade-levels">
                        <div class="grade-card">
                            <div class="grade-level">Elementary</div>
                            <div class="examples">
                                <strong>Remember:</strong> List three ways to create space in tag games<br>
                                <strong>Understand:</strong> Describe how heart rate changes during activity<br>
                                <strong>Apply:</strong> Use offense/defense concepts in simple games
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="grade-card">
                            <div class="grade-level">Middle School</div>
                            <div class="examples">
                                <strong>Analyze:</strong> Identify strengths and weaknesses in team strategy<br>
                                <strong>Evaluate:</strong> Judge the effectiveness of different warm-up routines<br>
                                <strong>Create:</strong> Develop a game modification for inclusive participation
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="grade-card">
                            <div class="grade-level">High School</div>
                            <div class="examples">
                                <strong>Understand:</strong> Explain FITT principles for cardiovascular fitness<br>
                                <strong>Analyze:</strong> Compare the energy systems used in different activities<br>
                                <strong>Evaluate:</strong> Critique fitness apps for accuracy and effectiveness
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Social Domain -->
            <div class="domain-card social">
                <div class="domain-badge">
                    <span class="domain-icon"></span>
                    Social Domain
                </div>
                <div class="definition">
                    The social domain addresses interpersonal skills, cooperation, and respectful interaction during physical activity. Students learn to work with others, communicate effectively, resolve conflicts, and demonstrate responsible personal and social behaviors.
                </div>
                
                <div class="bloom-section">
                    <div class="bloom-title">Bloom's Taxonomy in Action</div>
                    <div class="grade-levels">
                        <div class="grade-card">
                            <div class="grade-level">Elementary</div>
                            <div class="examples">
                                <strong>Remember:</strong> Identify fair play behaviors in games<br>
                                <strong>Apply:</strong> Work cooperatively with a partner during activities<br>
                                <strong>Analyze:</strong> Recognize when peers need encouragement or support
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="grade-card">
                            <div class="grade-level">Middle School</div>
                            <div class="examples">
                                <strong>Apply:</strong> Demonstrate leadership roles in small group activities<br>
                                <strong>Evaluate:</strong> Reflect on how your communication affected team success<br>
                                <strong>Create:</strong> Establish team agreements for respectful collaboration
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="grade-card">
                            <div class="grade-level">High School</div>
                            <div class="examples">
                                <strong>Analyze:</strong> Examine how cultural differences influence sport participation<br>
                                <strong>Evaluate:</strong> Assess conflict resolution strategies in competitive settings<br>
                                <strong>Create:</strong> Design inclusive activities that value diverse abilities
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Affective Domain -->
            <div class="domain-card affective">
                <div class="domain-badge">
                    <span class="domain-icon"></span>
                    Affective Domain
                </div>
                <div class="definition">
                    The affective domain involves personal attitudes, values, and emotions related to physical activity. Students develop self-confidence, intrinsic motivation, appreciation for movement, and the ability to regulate emotions during physical challenges.
                </div>
                
                <div class="bloom-section">
                    <div class="bloom-title">Bloom's Taxonomy in Action</div>
                    <div class="grade-levels">
                        <div class="grade-card">
                            <div class="grade-level">Elementary</div>
                            <div class="examples">
                                <strong>Receive:</strong> Listen to and acknowledge feedback on skill performance<br>
                                <strong>Respond:</strong> Show enthusiasm when trying new physical activities<br>
                                <strong>Value:</strong> Choose to participate in physical activity during free time
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="grade-card">
                            <div class="grade-level">Middle School</div>
                            <div class="examples">
                                <strong>Organize:</strong> Set personal fitness goals and track progress<br>
                                <strong>Characterize:</strong> Demonstrate self-management when facing challenges<br>
                                <strong>Value:</strong> Express enjoyment from mastering new skills
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="grade-card">
                            <div class="grade-level">High School</div>
                            <div class="examples">
                                <strong>Organize:</strong> Create a personal fitness philosophy based on values<br>
                                <strong>Characterize:</strong> Integrate regular physical activity into lifestyle<br>
                                <strong>Value:</strong> Advocate for inclusive physical activity opportunities
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Revised Bloom's Taxonomy Model -->
            <div class="objective-section" style="margin-top: 40px; background: linear-gradient(135deg, #fff8e1 0%, #ffe9a3 100%); border-color: #ffb71b;">
                <h2 style="color: #8b6914; margin-bottom: 20px;">Understanding Revised Bloom's Taxonomy for Physical Education</h2>
                <p style="color: #6b5416; margin-bottom: 20px; line-height: 1.7;">
                    Anderson and Krathwohl's (2001) revision of Bloom's Taxonomy redefines learning objectives as the intersection of two dimensions: the <strong>Cognitive Process Dimension</strong> (what students do) and the <strong>Knowledge Dimension</strong> (what students learn). This creates a powerful framework for writing clear, measurable PE objectives.
                </p>

                <div style="background: white; padding: 25px; border-radius: 10px; margin-bottom: 25px; border: 2px solid var(--uncg-blue-green);">
                    <h3 style="color: var(--uncg-blue-green); margin-top: 0;">The Two-Dimensional Framework</h3>
                    <p style="color: var(--text-medium); margin-bottom: 20px;">
                        <strong>A learning objective contains a VERB (cognitive process) + OBJECT (knowledge type)</strong>
                    </p>
                    
                    <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 20px; margin-top: 20px;">
                        <div style="background: #e8eef5; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid var(--uncg-blue);">
                            <h4 style="color: var(--uncg-blue); margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 15px;">Cognitive Process Dimension</h4>
                            <p style="color: #1f2937; font-size: 0.95em; margin-bottom: 10px;">From lower to higher order thinking:</p>
                            <div style="color: #1f2937; font-size: 0.9em; line-height: 1.8;">
                                <strong>1. Remember:</strong> recognize, recall<br>
                                <strong>2. Understand:</strong> interpret, exemplify, classify, summarize, infer, compare, explain<br>
                                <strong>3. Apply:</strong> execute, implement<br>
                                <strong>4. Analyze:</strong> differentiate, organize, attribute<br>
                                <strong>5. Evaluate:</strong> check, critique<br>
                                <strong>6. Create:</strong> generate, plan, produce
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <div style="background: #e0f5f5; padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid var(--uncg-blue-green);">
                            <h4 style="color: #2a7877; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 15px;">Knowledge Dimension</h4>
                            <p style="color: #1f2937; font-size: 0.95em; margin-bottom: 10px;">From concrete to abstract:</p>
                            <div style="color: #1f2937; font-size: 0.9em; line-height: 1.8;">
                                <strong>Factual:</strong> terminology, specific details<br>
                                <strong>Conceptual:</strong> classifications, principles, theories<br>
                                <strong>Procedural:</strong> skills, techniques, methods<br>
                                <strong>Metacognitive:</strong> strategic knowledge, self-knowledge
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <h3 style="color: #8b6914; margin-bottom: 20px;">Sample PE Objectives Using the Revised Taxonomy</h3>
                <p style="color: #6b5416; margin-bottom: 20px; font-size: 0.95em; font-style: italic;">
                    Each objective combines a cognitive process (verb) with a type of knowledge (object). The examples below show how different combinations create objectives at various cognitive levels and knowledge types:
                </p>

                <div style="overflow-x: auto;">
                    <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; background: white; border-radius: 8px; overflow: hidden;">
                        <thead>
                            <tr style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, var(--uncg-blue) 0%, var(--uncg-blue-green) 100%); color: white;">
                                <th style="padding: 15px; text-align: left; font-weight: 600; border-right: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.2);">Knowledge Type</th>
                                <th style="padding: 15px; text-align: left; font-weight: 600; border-right: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.2);">Remember</th>
                                <th style="padding: 15px; text-align: left; font-weight: 600; border-right: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.2);">Understand</th>
                                <th style="padding: 15px; text-align: left; font-weight: 600; border-right: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.2);">Apply</th>
                                <th style="padding: 15px; text-align: left; font-weight: 600; border-right: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.2);">Analyze</th>
                                <th style="padding: 15px; text-align: left; font-weight: 600; border-right: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.2);">Evaluate</th>
                                <th style="padding: 15px; text-align: left; font-weight: 600;">Create</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">
                                <td style="padding: 15px; font-weight: 600; color: var(--primary); background: #f8fafc;">Factual</td>
                                <td style="padding: 15px; font-size: 0.9em;">List primary locomotor skills</td>
                                <td style="padding: 15px; font-size: 0.9em;">Summarize features of cardiovascular fitness</td>
                                <td style="padding: 15px; font-size: 0.9em;">Respond to frequently asked questions about rules</td>
                                <td style="padding: 15px; font-size: 0.9em;">Select the most complete list of warm-up activities</td>
                                <td style="padding: 15px; font-size: 0.9em;">Check for consistency among fitness guidelines</td>
                                <td style="padding: 15px; font-size: 0.9em;">Generate a log of daily physical activities</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">
                                <td style="padding: 15px; font-weight: 600; color: var(--primary); background: #f8fafc;">Conceptual</td>
                                <td style="padding: 15px; font-size: 0.9em;">Recognize symptoms of dehydration</td>
                                <td style="padding: 15px; font-size: 0.9em;">Classify exercises by muscle groups targeted</td>
                                <td style="padding: 15px; font-size: 0.9em;">Provide advice to beginners about proper form</td>
                                <td style="padding: 15px; font-size: 0.9em;">Differentiate offensive and defensive strategies</td>
                                <td style="padding: 15px; font-size: 0.9em;">Determine relevance of research findings</td>
                                <td style="padding: 15px; font-size: 0.9em;">Assemble a team with complementary skills</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid #e5e7eb;">
                                <td style="padding: 15px; font-weight: 600; color: var(--primary); background: #f8fafc;">Procedural</td>
                                <td style="padding: 15px; font-size: 0.9em;">Recall how to perform chest compressions</td>
                                <td style="padding: 15px; font-size: 0.9em;">Clarify proper technique for overhand serve</td>
                                <td style="padding: 15px; font-size: 0.9em;">Carry out FITT principles in workout design</td>
                                <td style="padding: 15px; font-size: 0.9em;">Integrate safety procedures with game modifications</td>
                                <td style="padding: 15px; font-size: 0.9em;">Judge efficiency of different training methods</td>
                                <td style="padding: 15px; font-size: 0.9em;">Design an efficient warm-up routine</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td style="padding: 15px; font-weight: 600; color: var(--primary); background: #f8fafc;">Metacognitive</td>
                                <td style="padding: 15px; font-size: 0.9em;">Identify personal strategies for staying motivated</td>
                                <td style="padding: 15px; font-size: 0.9em;">Predict one's response to competitive pressure</td>
                                <td style="padding: 15px; font-size: 0.9em;">Use learning techniques that match one's strengths</td>
                                <td style="padding: 15px; font-size: 0.9em;">Deconstruct one's biases about certain activities</td>
                                <td style="padding: 15px; font-size: 0.9em;">Reflect on one's progress toward fitness goals</td>
                                <td style="padding: 15px; font-size: 0.9em;">Create a personalized learning portfolio</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>

                <div class="tips-box" style="margin-top: 25px; background: linear-gradient(135deg, #fff8e1 0%, #ffe9a3 100%);">
                    <div class="tips-title" style="color: #8b6914;">Key Insights for PE Objective Writing</div>
                    <ul style="color: #6b5416;">
                        <li><strong>Lower order thinking skills provide the foundation for higher order skills:</strong> Students need to remember and understand before they can effectively analyze, evaluate, and create</li>
                        <li><strong>Most learning activities involve multiple levels:</strong> A single PE lesson may include both lower and higher order thinking across different knowledge types</li>
                        <li><strong>The categories aren't always rigid:</strong> Some procedural knowledge can be as abstract as conceptual knowledge; analyzing can be as complex as creating depending on the context</li>
                        <li><strong>Start with "Students will be able to..."</strong> then add your verb (cognitive process) + object (knowledge)</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <p style="color: #6b5416; margin-top: 20px; font-size: 0.9em; font-style: italic;">
                    <strong>Reference:</strong> Anderson, L.W., Krathwohl, D.R., et al. (2001). <em>A taxonomy for learning, teaching, and assessing: A revision of Bloom's Taxonomy of Educational Objectives.</em> New York: Longman.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="tab-content">
            <h2>Writing Effective Lesson Objectives</h2>
            <p style="margin-bottom: 30px; color: var(--text-medium); font-size: 1.05em;">
                Strong lesson objectives clearly communicate what students will learn and be able to demonstrate by the end of the lesson. Using the "The Learner Will Be Able To" (TLWBAT) format ensures objectives are student-centered, measurable, and aligned with the learning domains.
            </p>

            <div class="objective-section">
                <h3>The TLWBAT Formula</h3>
                <div class="formula-box">
                    <div class="formula-text">The Learner Will Be Able To + [Action Verb] + [Content/Skill] + [Condition/Context]</div>
                    
                    <div class="formula-parts">
                        <div class="formula-part">
                            <div class="formula-label">Action Verb</div>
                            <div class="formula-example">Measurable, observable action from Bloom's Taxonomy (demonstrate, explain, create, analyze)</div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="formula-part">
                            <div class="formula-label">Content/Skill</div>
                            <div class="formula-example">Specific skill, concept, or behavior to be learned (forehand stroke, cardiovascular fitness, teamwork)</div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="formula-part">
                            <div class="formula-label">Condition/Context</div>
                            <div class="formula-example">Circumstances or criteria for performance (during a game, with 80% accuracy, in pairs)</div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="tips-box">
                    <div class="tips-title">Tips for Writing Strong Objectives</div>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Use specific, measurable verbs</strong> â€“ Choose action verbs that describe observable behaviors (demonstrate, identify, create) rather than vague terms (understand, know, appreciate)</li>
                        <li><strong>Align with the learning domain</strong> â€“ Make sure your verb and content match the domain you're targeting (psychomotor, cognitive, social, or affective)</li>
                        <li><strong>Keep it student-focused</strong> â€“ The objective describes what students will do, not what the teacher will teach</li>
                        <li><strong>Include meaningful context</strong> â€“ Add conditions that clarify the level of mastery or setting (e.g., "in a small-sided game," "with a partner," "with 70% success rate")</li>
                        <li><strong>Make it achievable within the lesson</strong> â€“ Objectives should be realistic for one class period, not goals that take weeks to accomplish</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="objective-section">
                <h3>Objective Examples by Domain</h3>
                <div class="objective-examples">
                    <div class="objective-card psychomotor">
                        <div class="objective-domain">Psychomotor</div>
                        <div class="objective-text">
                            "TLWBAT demonstrate a mature overhand throwing pattern with proper step opposition, trunk rotation, and follow-through during partner toss activities."
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="objective-card psychomotor">
                        <div class="objective-domain">Psychomotor</div>
                        <div class="objective-text">
                            "TLWBAT execute three different volleyball passes (bump, set, spike) with appropriate form during modified game play."
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="objective-card cognitive">
                        <div class="objective-domain">Cognitive</div>
                        <div class="objective-text">
                            "TLWBAT explain the relationship between heart rate and exercise intensity by comparing resting, moderate, and vigorous activity levels."
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="objective-card cognitive">
                        <div class="objective-domain">Cognitive</div>
                        <div class="objective-text">
                            "TLWBAT analyze offensive and defensive strategies in basketball and identify three tactical decisions that impact game outcomes."
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="objective-card social">
                        <div class="objective-domain">Social</div>
                        <div class="objective-text">
                            "TLWBAT work cooperatively with classmates of varying skill levels by encouraging teammates and offering constructive feedback during small-sided games."
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="objective-card social">
                        <div class="objective-domain">Social</div>
                        <div class="objective-text">
                            "TLWBAT demonstrate effective communication skills by using clear, respectful language when resolving conflicts or disagreements during team activities."
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="objective-card affective">
                        <div class="objective-domain">Affective</div>
                        <div class="objective-text">
                            "TLWBAT demonstrate perseverance by continuing to attempt challenging skills even after initial unsuccessful trials, reflecting on personal progress."
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="objective-card affective">
                        <div class="objective-domain">Affective</div>
                        <div class="objective-text">
                            "TLWBAT identify personal feelings about physical activity participation and express one reason why physical activity is valuable to them."
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="objective-section">
                <h3>Common Bloom's Taxonomy Action Verbs by Domain</h3>
                <p style="margin-bottom: 20px; color: var(--text-medium);">Use these domain-appropriate verbs to create clear, measurable objectives:</p>
                
                <div class="grade-levels">
                    <div class="grade-card">
                        <div class="grade-level" style="color: var(--psychomotor);">Psychomotor</div>
                        <div class="examples">
                            Demonstrate, perform, execute, dribble, throw, catch, jump, balance, strike, kick, run, dance, manipulate, coordinate
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="grade-card">
                        <div class="grade-level" style="color: #0f2044;">Cognitive</div>
                        <div class="examples">
                            Explain, identify, analyze, describe, compare, evaluate, create, design, list, classify, distinguish, formulate, predict
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="grade-card">
                        <div class="grade-level" style="color: #2d7a5f;">Social</div>
                        <div class="examples">
                            Cooperate, collaborate, communicate, share, assist, encourage, lead, follow, resolve, negotiate, support, respect, participate
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="grade-card">
                        <div class="grade-level" style="color: #8b6914;">Affective</div>
                        <div class="examples">
                            Value, appreciate, express, demonstrate (self-control), reflect, commit, advocate, choose, persist, embrace, prioritize, regulate
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="tab-content">
            <h2>Test Your Knowledge: Match Objectives to Standards</h2>
            <p style="margin-bottom: 30px; color: var(--text-medium); font-size: 1.05em;">
                Practice identifying which of the four 2024 SHAPE America National PE Standards each lesson objective aligns with. This low-stakes quiz helps you develop the skill of analyzing objectives and connecting them to the appropriate standard.
            </p>

            <div class="quiz-container">
                <div id="quiz-header" style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #0f2044 0%, #1a2f5a 100%); color: white; padding: 25px; border-radius: 12px; margin-bottom: 30px;">
                    <div style="display: flex; justify-content: space-between; align-items: center; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 15px;">
                        <div>
                            <div style="font-size: 0.9em; opacity: 0.9; margin-bottom: 5px;">Question <span id="current-question">1</span> of <span id="total-questions">10</span></div>
